}

}
}

comment_text:
14:57 for anybody wondering(and this is why I think it is):-

1 byte = 8 bits

Let this(8 box pack) represent a "byte" where each box denotes a "bit"(binary digit aka 0 or 1)
‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢‚ñ¢

Now, if we use the first box to store the sign of the number(+ve, -ve), we`re left with 7 boxes to represent a decimal number in binary representation using 0s and 1s
The total number of individual ways in which we can arrange 0s and 1s in the 7 boxes to form a unique number OR the total number of possible decimal numbers we can represent is-

2^7 (2x2x2x2x2x2x2) <2 coz binary digits are just 2 ie 0 and 1 and we have two options to fill each of the seven boxes>

2^7 = 128
and with the one box we left for holding the sign, we can basically store 128 negative numbers(-1 to -128) and 128 positive numbers(0 to 127)
[0 can have any sign in ordinary mathematics so whatever] and if you`re really wondering about it-
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33159303/in-signed-primitives-is-0-positive-or-negative-or-both

PS- Don`t come after me for having explained a silly thing üíÄ

comment_text:
Java Statement Types.


Type of statements in java

In Java, there are several types of statements that can be used to perform different operations. Some of the most common types of statements in Java include:

Expression Statements: These statements are used to evaluate an expression and can include method calls, assignments, and other operations.

Declaration Statements: These statements are used to declare a new variable or constant and specify its type.

Control Flow Statements: These statements are used to control the flow of execution in a program, including if-else statements, switch statements, loops (for, while, do-while), and try-catch statements.

Jump Statements: These statements allow the program to jump to a specific part of the code, including break, continue, and return statements.

Assertion Statements: These statements are used to check assumptions made by the programmer and throw an error if the assertion fails.

Synchronized Statements: These statements are used to control access to shared resources in a multithreaded environment.

Labeled Statements: These statements are used to provide a label to a block of code, which can be used for easy navigation and readability.

Block Statements: These statements are used to group a set of statements together, which can be treated as a single unit for control flow or variable scoping.

comment_text:
Generalized formula: -
Firstly consider the how many bytes that particular data type takes, suppose taking 'int' as an example, it take 4 bytes which is equals to
(8*4 = 32 bits) [1 byte = 8 bit] so the generalized formula will be [-2^n/2 to 2^n/2 -1], here n is the number of bits.....
Considering our example of int data type the generalized formula will be [-2^32/2 to 2^32-1] on further calculation it will be ranging between
[-2147483648 to 2147483647].
Hope it helps :D
Cleaned_Comment: Generalized formula Firstly consider the how many bytes that particular data type takes suppose taking 39int39 as an example it take 4 bytes which is equals to 84 32 bits 1 byte 8 bit so the generalized formula will be 2n2 to 2n2 1 here n is the number of bitsConsidering our example of int data type the generalized formula will be 2322 to 2321 on further calculation it will be ranging between 2147483648 to 2147483647Hope it helps D

import java.util.Scanner;

public class App {
public static void main(String[] args) {
Scanner numScanner = new Scanner(System.in);
byte byteNum = 8;
System.out.print("Enter the primitive data type byte value: ");
int valueRange = numScanner.nextInt() * byteNum;
long algo1 = (Math.round(Math.pow(valueRange, 2)) / 2);
long algo2 = (Math.round(Math.pow(valueRange, 2)) / 2);

System.out.println("Value ranges from: -" + algo1 + " to " + (algo2 - 1));
}
}
